\begin_layout Subsection
Status implied by status goods and wealth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first question that we must clarify is whether status goods are used
 to indicate higher status by those having higher status or are by those
 who don't have higher status? Since status goods arise out of competition
 - there are reasons to be believe both of these are true.
 It is why Veblen also considers both individious comparison (IC) and pecuniary
 emulation (PE) important towards conspicuous consumption (for which I have
 used a more general definition of status consumption).
 The two mechanisms of IC and PE are however theoretical constructs - that
 the behavioural sciences (or any perspective with a descriptive concern)
 could contend since them consumer hardly ever know the reason why they
 purchase status goods.
 It could even be said that status competitions thrives in the ambiguity
 over who has higher status.
 The modern interpretation of status consumption is its view as a currency
 in status competitions.
 Since competitions vary by social contexts, the issue of a reference point
 is key to the definition of status consumption and goods.
 Thus, one does not expect status competitions to ensue between two consumers
 with extreme social-economic or cultural differences (i.e.
 disjoint reference points) who are aware of the extreme differences.
 Notice all that if "status" were a prerequisite for participating in status
 competitions i.e.
 if only those with status needed to spend on status goods, we would see
 no status consumption in societies as they moved towards equality.
 As Hirsch notes, the improvement in median incomes seems to have increased
 the focus on status items in the developed world.
 This is an agreement with the competition view of status since with less
 income differences in an economy, status goods are all what consumers can
 use to participate in competitions for status.
 
\end_layout

