\begin_layout Standard
Does status consumption increases one's probability or instead does perceived
 probability cause status consumption.
 The effect of status consumption is not measurable - i.e.
 we don't measure how much status consumption improves one's income.
 It is the latter that existence of competition requires one to increase
 status consumption.
 A certain probability of transition from wealth bands is therefore reflected
 in status consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Does status consumption change real probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No.
 In the short run, it does not make any difference - how could status consumptio
n change the exogenous probability of asset transition? They change the
 interaction and position consumers but their long-term effects are slow
 (not immediate) and occur with other changes.
 The tendencies to compete within one's group are innate - and we don't
 really participate with a known probability to win.
 What is certain however, is that we like being ahead of others.
 We are a competitive species and are wired for trying to get ahead of others
 who we see and interact with.
 Again, non-durable status consumption is futile except as external needs
 of the consumer.
 While we may call status consumption futile, we can't ignore the fact that
 the consumers get utility as direct value from status consumption with
 respect to a reference - which we infer with asset bands.
 
\end_layout

